value.Title: ATF Fully Mobile Workforce Implementation Devices and Telecomm
value.Details_x0020_of_x0020_Strategy: The ATF Fully Mobile Workforce Implementation Devices and Telecomm describe ATF's effort in moving towards providing IT and telecom solutions to its employees outside of the typical office setting.  This is being achieved through the deployment of iPhones to ATF's Special Agents and Industry Operations Investigators allowing access to email and various data sets.  A smaller group of field and HQ personnel have also been provided iPads for the same reason.
value.Use_x0020_of_x0020_Savings_x002f0: The use of cost of avoidance from this savings initiative will assist ATF to provide critical services during the sequestration period and beyond.

value.Title: ATF Service Delivery Implementation
value.Details_x0020_of_x0020_Strategy: ATF expects program efficiencies (cost reductions) resulting from full implementation of the ESA IV contract service delivery model, which includes greater reliance on virtualization, more cost effective end user devices, and an overall more efficient service delivery resulting in lower costs per user. This strategy includes cost effective seat management of leased end-user client workstations.
value.Use_x0020_of_x0020_Savings_x002f0: The use of cost of avoidance from this savings initiative will enable ATF in providing critical services during the out years. It is not possible at this time to reflect what cost savings we may experience as an ROI for services and equipment that were so drastically cut. We expect that future figures may show an increase in the overall budget due to the baseline created by the sequestration actions.

value.Title: BOP Cisco Maintenance Agreement
value.Details_x0020_of_x0020_Strategy: The strategy used was leveraging the use of other DOJ component's purchasing vehicle. As a result of DOJ's implementation of a Vendor Management program across all components, BOP was aware of FBI's contract for CISCO equipment and decided to use that vehicle for its annual renewal
value.Use_x0020_of_x0020_Savings_x002f0: Savings will be used towards expansion of the VOIP evaluation presently underway within BOP

value.Title: JMD Consolidation of Land Mobile Radio Systems / Contracts
value.Details_x0020_of_x0020_Strategy: The Department's Land Mobile Radio (LMR) program aims to achieve cost avoidance by driving down per unit costs when procuring equipment and services by leveraging the Department's combined competitive purchasing power and utilizing shared system solutions. The savings were obtained by consolidating purchasing of radio and associated equipment off a single strategic contract.
value.Use_x0020_of_x0020_Savings_x002f0: Savings used to continue nationwide LMR deployment

value.Title: DEA - Mainframe (formerly M204)
value.Details_x0020_of_x0020_Strategy: A DEA analysis conducted in early 2012 recommended that all M-204 applications and data that currently reside within the DOJ IBM mainframe environment be migrated to other DEA specific platforms and/or applications and the Enterprise Data Warehouse.  The analysis reflected a major overhead cost savings of millions of dollars for DEA if all M-204 applications are migrated off the DOJ IBM mainframe. DEA is currently beginning year 2 of a 3 year strategy to migrate all applications off the mainframe.  When completed, the cost savings will be approximately $13 million per year.
value.Use_x0020_of_x0020_Savings_x002f0: Any cost savings generated from this initiative will be reprioritized based on DEA's zero based budget process and be used to meet DEA's mission and goals.

value.Title: DEA Next Generation Network
value.Details_x0020_of_x0020_Strategy: The Next Generation Network (NGN) will migrate DEA from two physically separate networks for Firebird and Spider to two virtual networks sharing a common physical infrastructure.  NGN will provide both wired and wireless access using IEEE 802.1x, MAC Authentication Bypass (MAB), and Web Authentication for Network Admission Control (NAC).  DEA plans to have 1 site converted by end of FY 2014 as part of a pilot.  After that, implementation would follow a 5 year refresh cycle ending in FY 2020.
value.Use_x0020_of_x0020_Savings_x002f0: Any cost savings generated from this initiative will be reprioritized based on DEA's zero based budget process and be used to meet DEA's mission and goals.

value.Title: DEA Printer Management
value.Details_x0020_of_x0020_Strategy: DEA is embarking on a print management initiative that entails several components designed to better utilize DEA's print capabilities and install policies that will reduce both the number of printers and the number of pages being printed. Tasks include: (1) changing the printer to user ratio to meet the industry norm, (2) Right-size printer capacity to match the needs of the office in which the printer resides; (3) PIV enable network printers; (4) Purchase multi-functional devices instead of separate printers and scanners; (5) Reduce the amount of power (footprint) required to operate the printers; and (6) Implement printer management software to track print jobs and enable print policy to reduce printing throughout DEA. This initiative is currently in a pilot phase and will be rolled out to the entire agency in the next 2-3 years. When fully implemented, the cost avoidance is estimated to be approximately $3 million per year.
value.Use_x0020_of_x0020_Savings_x002f0: Any cost avoidance generated from this initiative will offset cuts to DEA's IT program. Estimate using avoidance for additional procurement and rollout (25% in FY14, 25% in FY15, etc).

value.Title: JMD DOJ Federation Service
value.Details_x0020_of_x0020_Strategy: The DOJ Federation Service is a centralized security token service that provides cross-domain security authentication of users to trusted claims-enabled applications. Cost avoidance is achieved through reduced helpdesk support in administering user identities within each application that utilizes the service for user authentication. The DOJ Federation Service achieved IOC in July 2012, and identity providers continue to be on-boarded (over 20 DOJ Components including an external agency are using the service) to broker single sign-on to various applications. These applications (hosted by DOJ on premises and in the Cloud) in addition to externally hosted applications (e.g., OMB) accept the security tokens for authentication. Additional cost avoidance will be achieved as other identity providers and applications continue to be on-boarded throughout 2015.
value.Commodity_x0020_IT_x0020_Categor: IT Security (Not Identity and Access Management)
value.Use_x0020_of_x0020_Savings_x002f0: The savings/avoidance is achieved through reduced helpdesk support in administering user identities within each application that utilizes the service for user authentication, and as other identity providers and applications continue to be on-boarded.

value.Title: JMD Email Consolidation
value.Details_x0020_of_x0020_Strategy: The purpose of this strategy is to consolidate email systems. Phase 1 of the email consolidation project is to consolidate 14 email systems into one.  Specifically, 14 offices, encompassing approximately 20,000 users and their corresponding email addresses, will be migrated onto a single contractor-managed platform.  As part of the Phase 1 project, the existing email system, "JCON Mail", will be decommissioned and generating savings starting in FY2014.  Phase 1 started in October 2012.  Migrations are occurring in waves with the first wave in the Spring 2013 and the last in the Fall/Winter 2014.

To manage the various data stores as well as mirror the data natively for COOP requirements, ENRD leveraged its 2013 network procurement by deploying a  Cisco/NetApp/VMWare Flexpod storage solution
value.Use_x0020_of_x0020_Savings_x002f0: The Flexpod implementation and installation will continue into FY 15. We expect once the network infrastructure is in place, cost avoidance/cost saving options will be available.

value.Title: JMD Enterprise Mobility Infrastructure
value.Details_x0020_of_x0020_Strategy: A key element of the Department's mobility strategy is the shared service Mobile Device Management (MDM) platform, which supports 12 components, avoiding duplicate systems across groups and providing an annual cost avoidance. This strategy began implementation in FY13 and is continuing into FY14.
value.Use_x0020_of_x0020_Savings_x002f0: Reinvested in mobility commodity

value.Title: JMD Enterprise Personnel Security System (JSTARS)
value.Details_x0020_of_x0020_Strategy: This strategy involves building and deploying a DOJ enterprise personnel security system (JSTARS) to manage processing of background investigations, clearances, reinvestigations and special compartmental information access authorization.  This strategy will retire and replace existing systems in use by DOJ components and avoid build out cost of these systems to comply with directives from the DNI/OPM, Joint Reform Team for compliance to the Intelligence Reform and Terrorism Prevention Act of 2005, NIST security standards, etc.  IOC for enterprise system achieved June, 2011.  FOC achieved October 2012 after all data migrated and consolidated.  Savings include estimated O&M costs from systems retirement of several systems and DME cost avoidance to build out these systems to compliance standards.  Savings do not include savings from re-use of existing (reciprocal) investigations, time savings of increased throughput, paperless case files, and automation of processing and correspondence.

value.Title: USA Efficiencies - Toners and EVoIP

value.Title: DOJ Data Center Transformation Initiative (DCTI)
value.Details_x0020_of_x0020_Strategy:
The Data Center Transformation Initiative (DCTI) represents DOJs strategic enterprise-wide approach to serve each components mission needs through adaptable enterprise IT services while striving for greater IT efficiencies. DCTI will establish hybrid services and infrastructure -- on-premise, outsourced, and cloud -- to best deliver commodity IT capabilities for DOJs diverse missions of law enforcement, litigation, and incarceration.  

Goals and objectives for DCTI include:

 Optimize and standardize IT infrastructure to improve operational efficiencies and agility
 Reduce the energy and real property footprint of DOJs data center facilities 
 Optimize the use of IT staff and labor resources supporting DOJ missions
 Enhance DOJs IT security posture

Savings figures are reported as gross savings, as they do not include costs required to achieve consolidation/optimization.

value.Title: JMD Strategic Sourcing:  Contract Escalator Reductions / IT Procurement Process Improvements
value.Details_x0020_of_x0020_Strategy:
This cost savings strategy is part of the larger initiative to stand up a vendor management office to perform IT strategic sourcing.  A successful first activity of the team was the elimination of escalation costs for FY13 on one of the Department's enterprise-wide contracts called "ITSS-4".  The contracting team for this Department-wide Blanket Purchase Agreement (BPA) approached all of the vendors to discuss budget realities and requested their consideration on holding billing rates flat for task option years.  Vendors also committed to a critical review of cost proposals on new task orders as well.  Net savings for 2013 are $1.13M with no investment funding required.  Flattened costs in FY 2013 reduce total contract costs even if contractors implement escalation costs in future years due to the compounding nature of annual escalation percentages.

Additional savings resulting from:

- Army waiving 1% fee on Oracle renewals in FY13, savings of $0.155
- ITSS-4 vendors maintaining FY12 rates on existing tasks orders for OBDs in FY13, avoidance of $0.876
- Training offer from FranklinCovey for the Justice Management Division (JMD) in FY13, negotiated a savings of $0.630
-  Reduced IBM security proposal price through negotiations in Fy14, savings of $0.600

value.Title: JMD Eliminate JABS Help Desk
value.Details_x0020_of_x0020_Strategy: During FY 13 JABS developed self help interfaces that allows a user to unlock an account through standard "secret question" dialogs, and interfaces that use federated ID and trusted broker technologies to automate new account creation. By changing the user-facing help policy to force the first user call to the component help desk, JABS was able to eliminate the unnecessary calls to JABS and provide the component help desks with easy ways to refer users to solutions to all types of calls that do not require JABS-specific expertise. value.Title: JMD Treasury Address Request (TAR) Program
value.Details_x0020_of_x0020_Strategy:
Establishes access for the Department of Justices Debt Collection Management Staff to the Treasury Address Request (TAR) program to facilitate address validation in a shorter period of time, using fewer resources.

Previously when a collection office (USAO, or Private Counsel) received a referral from the Nationwide Central Intake Facility (NCIF), each office used publicly available records or other techniques to ascertain the current addresses of individuals who owe debts to the United States.  This imposed significant costs and administrative burdens that could prevent or delay the collection process.

The TAR program provides a means to centralize the address search/validation process.  Under the program, the NCIF sends a file from the Consolidated Debt Collection System to the Internal Revenue Service (IRS) to obtain the last known address the debtor provided to the IRS.  This program reduces the time and resources required to obtain valid address information and locate the debtor.
value.Use_x0020_of_x0020_Savings_x002f0: Reinvested into program

value.Title: JMD Refer Eligible Civil Debts from Private Counsel Offices to the Treasury Offset Program
value.Details_x0020_of_x0020_Strategy:
This program establishes a process for Private Counsel (PC) offices, under contract with the Department of Justice (DOJ), to refer eligible civil debts to the Treasury Offset Program (TOP). 
The Department of Treasury, Financial Management Service, operates TOP, which is a centralized offset program used to collect delinquent debts owed to federal agencies.   The Debt Collection Management Staff (DCM), Justice Management Division, manages this program for DOJ and routinely refers debts handled by the U.S. Attorneys Offices (USAO) to TOP once a judgment has been obtained and other basic Treasury mandated criteria have been met.  In addition to the debts handled by the USAOs, DOJ contracts with PCs to litigate and collect debt on behalf of the United States.  Historically, DCM has not referred to TOP debts being handled by PCs, largely due to contractual constraints impacting administration of the program.  

With the resolution of contractual issues, DCM began referring all Private Counsel debts (post-judgment) to TOP in FY2014.   This occurred during the 1st Quarter, FY 2014, following enhancements to both systems in DCM (Consolidated Debt Collection System and Debt Management Module) and sufficient notification to both Private Counsel as well as the debtors.

ATF expects efficiencies resulting from nationwide deployment of VoIP and complete elimination of local phone line charges and interoffice long distance charges. Annual savings are contingent upon completing the requested reinvestment in VoIP infrastructure installation. ATF expects efficiencies resulting from nationwide deployment of VoIP and complete elimination of local phone line charges and interoffice long distance charges. value.Title: CIV Point to Point Wireless Data Network
value.Details_x0020_of_x0020_Strategy: The Justice Unified Telecommunications Network (JUTNet) has proven to be overpriced at a given speed, with no satisfactory justification for it.  In addition, network traffic between buildings within the downtown DC area, where the Civil Division is a tenant, has no need to leave the control of the DOJ.  With those two drivers in mind, the Civil Division has stood up a Point to Point Wireless Data Network.  This network directly connects many of the buildings where the Civil Division is a tenant, at a speed of at least 1 Gbps.  The beauty of this system is that after the initial cost to acquire and install the equipment, only a relatively small support contract remains and needs to be renewed.  Meaning after the initial purchase, the cost avoidance begins.

value.Title: FBI Next Generation Identification
value.Details_x0020_of_x0020_Strategy: NGI designed, developed, and deployed IBM x86 hardware.  The original NGI hardware was deployed in 2009 and became end of life in 2014.  Early in 2014, the sale of IBM x86 blade line to Lenovo was announced. Lenovo is a Chinese owned company which restricted the FBI from purchasing equipment from them.  A legal agreement required IBM to maintain deployed IBM assets for 5 years from the date of sale.  The IBM/Lenovo sale was completed October 1, 2014.  US Intel Community restricted purchases of IBM Blades after completion of sale.  The NGI program explored mitigation options and negotiated with FBI/LM/IBM a full 1 for 1 replacement of NGI hardware and 5 years of maintenance at a substantial discount of $25 million.  The LM modification was signed on September 30, 2014.  IBM sourced world-wide and used maintenance build line to fill the FBI's order.  All NGI hardware was refreshed by May 2015 and will be come end of life October 2019.
